title: Long-range particles from nuclear fission

x4freetext: Long-range particles from nuclear fission

x4codes.hlp: Los Alamos National Laboratory, NM, United States of America

x4freetext: The probability of long-range particle
emission measured by four parallel-plate ionization
chambers operating in an argon plus 5% CO2 gas mixture.
The energy spectrum of long-range particles measured by
CsI crystal scintillation-spectrometer apparatus
consisted of a fission source deposited on a
100-mu-g/cm2 nickel foil symmetrically positioned with
respect to two sets of diametrically opposed
thallium-activated CsI crystals, viewed by
photomultiplier tubes through MgO2-surfaced vacuum
light pipes.  Two crystals were 2 cm in diameter and
0.41 mm in thickness, another two crystals were of the
same diameter and 0.076-mm in thickness, used in two
fold coincidence as fission detectors. These fission
detectors were covered with 100-mu-g/cm2 nickel-foil
light shields to prevent `crosstalk` with the
long-range particle crystals. The energy resolution of
the long-range particle counters was about 11% for
6.1 MeV 252Cf alphas and 6% for 8.78 MeV alphas from
212Po. The fluorescent response of CsI crystals to
alpha particles was determined by the use of alpha
particles both from natural radioactivity and from the
Los Alamos variable-energy cyclotron.
Long-range particles, which are known to be
predominantly alpha particles.

x4freetext: ARB-UNITS correspond counts per energy interval
The Cf252 source was prepared by autodeposition from
an intense parent source. Deposits were made on
100-mu-g/cm2 nickel foil which in some cases was
reinforced by a backing of 20-mesh, 93%- transparent,
`electromesh` nickel screen. Amount of active
material about 10.E-3 mu-g, spontaneous fission
rate - 3.E4 fissions/min.
Fig.5 from Phys.Rev.,126,1508,1962 digitized by
GSYS2.4.7.
